According to Fig. 3
                        A, as DIS concentration increases from 10 to 600 ng mL−1, the fluorescence responses of N.C-dots decreased gradually. The plot between the F˚/F ratio and different DIS concentration shows a strong linear dependence (F°/F = 0.074X + 0.16, r2 = 0.9987), where F and F° represent the fluorescence response of N.C-dots with and without DIS, respectively. The detection limit (S/N = 3) was estimated as 5.2 ng mL−1 (Table 1
                        ). In order to study the influence of DIS concentration on the oxidation peak currents. Under optimum conditions, SWV scans of DIS were recorded in the concentration range of 0.1 – 12 μg mL−1 at N.C-dots /CPE as presented in Fig. 3B. The response in the case of the first and second peak is almost equal, with a slight increase in the response of the first peak. Therefore, it was sufficient to make the calibration calculations on the first peak. The calibration plot for P1 was described by the following equation: IP1 (µA) = 3.61 + 8.43C (μg mL−1) (r2 = 0.9981) (Table 1).
